Continuous Random Data

Monika Peteva Petkova

mpetevap@uni-sofia.bg, monikapetevapetkova@gmail.com

2021

In statistics there are \(3\) types of random variables:

  • Discrete /Дискретни/
  • Continuous /Непрекъснати/
  • Mixtures /Смеси/

In this course we are going to review only the first two.

Let’s first explain some terms that we will need to use.

  • For discrete random variable:
    • Probability mass function (PMF) /Ред на разпределение/ - is a function that gives the probability that a discrete random variable is exactly equal to some value. \[P_X(x_i) := P(X = x_i)\] Example \[P_X(x_i) = P(X = x_i) = \begin{cases} 0.2, & x_i = 1 \\ 0.5, & x_i = 3 \\ 0.3, & x_i = 7 \\ 0, & otherwise \end{cases}\]
* **Cumulative distribution function (CDF) /Кумулативна функция на разпределение/** - is the probability that a random variable $X$ will take a value less than or equal to $x$.

\[F_X(x) := P(X \leq x) = \sum_{i: x_i \leq x}P(X = x_i)\]

Example:

  • For absolutely continuous random variable:
    • Probability density function (PDF) /Плътност на разпределение/ - If the probability density function \(f_X(x)\) exist, it is a non-negative function such that: \[F_X(x_0) = \int_{-\infty}^{x_0}f_X(x)dx\] and \[\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f_X(x)dx = 1\]
    • Cumulative distribution function (CDF) /Кумулативна функция на разпределение/ - is the probability that a random variable \(X\) will take a value less than or equal to \(x\). \[F_X(x) := P(X \leq x)\]
  • Moments - quantitative measures related to the shape of the function
    • First moment /Expectation, Mean/ \[\mu = E[X] = \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}{xdF_X(x)}\]
    • Second central moment /Variance/ \[\sigma^2 = Var[X] = D[X] = E[(X - E[X])^2] = \] \[= E[X^2 - 2XE[X] + (E[X])^2] = \] \[= E[X^2] - 2E[X]E[X] + (E[X])^2 = \] \[= E[X^2] - (E[X])^2\]
    • Third standardized moment /Skewness/ \[\operatorname{E}\left[\left(\frac{X - \mu}{\sigma}\right)^3 \right] = \frac{E(X - \mu)^3}{\sigma^3}\]
      We also say that the data on the first graphic is left-skewed and the data on the second graphic is right-skewed.
    • Fourth standardized moment \[\operatorname{E}\left[\left(\frac{X - \mu}{\sigma}\right)^4 \right] = \frac{E(X - \mu)^4}{\sigma^4}\] \[\text{Kurtosis} = \text{Fourth standardized moment} - 3\]
    They are also named: Mesokurtic /Normal/, Leptokurtic, Platykurtic

Continuous Ditributions

Continuous uniform distribution /Непрекъснато равномерно разпределение/

\[X \in U(a, b)\] \[X \in Unif(a, b)\] If we choose a point \(M\) at random in the interval between \(a\) and \(b\) and \(X\) is the length of the interval between \(M\) and \(a\) by geometric definition of probability for \(x \in [a, b]\)

\[P(X \leq x) = \frac{x - a}{b - a}\]

therefore

Cumulative distribution function (CDF) is \[F_X(x) = P(X \leq x) = \begin{cases} 0, & x < a \\ \frac{x-a}{b-a}, & x \in [a, b] \\ 1, & x > b \end{cases}\]

For \(p \in (0,1]\) the corresponding

\[\frac{x-a}{b-a} = p\] \[x-a = p(b-a)\] \[x = p(b-a) + a\]

Quantile function is \[X_p = F_X^{\leftarrow}(p) = min\{x \in \mathbb{R} : P(X \leq x) \geq p\} = p(b-a) + a\]

As far as the cumulative distribution function (CDF) is differentiable in \((a,b)\)

Probability density function (PDF) is \[f_X(x) = \begin{cases} \frac{1}{b-a}, & x \in [a, b] \\ 0, & otherwise \end{cases}\]

Mean /First initial moment/ \[\mu = E[X] = \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}{xdF_X(x)} = \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}{xf_X(x)dx} = \] \[= \int_{-\infty}^{a}{xf_X(x)dx} + \int_{a}^{b}{xf_X(x)dx} + \int_{b}^{+\infty}{xf_X(x)dx} = \] \[= \int_{-\infty}^{a}{x*0 \: dx} + \int_{a}^{b}{x \frac{1}{b-a} dx} + \int_{b}^{+\infty}{x * 0 \: dx} = \] \[= \frac{1}{b-a} \int_{a}^{b}{x dx} =\frac{1}{b-a} \frac{x^2}{2}|_a^b = \] \[ = \frac{1}{b-a} \left(\frac{b^2}{2} - \frac{a^2}{2}\right) = \] \[ = \frac{a+b}{2}\]

Second initial moment \[E[X^2] = \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}{x^2dF_X(x)} = \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}{x^2f_X(x)dx} = \] \[= \int_{-\infty}^{a}{x^2f_X(x)dx} + \int_{a}^{b}{x^2f_X(x)dx} + \int_{b}^{+\infty}{x^2f_X(x)dx} = \] \[= \int_{-\infty}^{a}{x^2*0 \: dx} + \int_{a}^{b}{x^2 \frac{1}{b-a} dx} + \int_{b}^{+\infty}{x^2 * 0 \: dx} = \] \[= \frac{1}{b-a} \int_{a}^{b}{x^2 dx} =\frac{1}{b-a} \frac{x^3}{3}|_a^b = \frac{1}{b-a} \left(\frac{b^3}{3} - \frac{a^3}{3}\right) = \] \[ = \frac{a^2+ab+b^2}{3}\]

Variance \[\sigma^2 = D[X] = E[X^2] - (E[X])^2 = \] \[ = \frac{a^2+ab+b^2}{3} - \frac{(a+b)^2}{4} = \] \[ = \frac{(b - a)^2}{12}\] Similarly we can use the functions dunif, runif, punif and qunif to find the theoretical probability density function, to generate random numbers, to find the cumulative distribution function and quantiles of continuous uniform distributed variable.

Let’s generate a realization of continuous \(Unif(0, 2)\) random variable.

> runif(1, min = 0, max = 2)
[1] 0.5815145

Let’s generate \(5\) realizations of continuous \(Unif(0, 2)\) random variable.

> runif(5, min = 0, max = 2)
[1] 1.401847 1.129311 1.207975 1.917698 1.185656

Let’s generate \(100\) realizations of continuous \(Unif(0, 2)\) random variable.

> x <- runif(100, min = 0, max = 2)
> hist(x, probability = TRUE, 
+      main = "Continuous uniform on [0,2]",
+      col = gray(.9))

> hist(x, probability = TRUE,
+      main = "Continuous uniform on [0,2]",
+      col = gray(.9))
> curve(dunif(x, min = 0, max = 2),
+       add = TRUE,
+       col = 2)

We can calculate the skewness and kurtosis of the sample using the skewness and kurtosis from EnvStats package.

> library(EnvStats)
Warning: package 'EnvStats' was built under R version 4.0.3

Attaching package: 'EnvStats'
The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':

    predict, predict.lm
The following object is masked from 'package:base':

    print.default
> skewness(x)
[1] 0.09564412
> kurtosis(x)
[1] -1.397842

As we can see the skewness is close to \(0\), because the uniform distribution is symmetric. As far as the kurtosis is negatite, the distribution is platykurtic.

Knowing that the random variable follows \(X \in Unif(0,1)\) distribution we can also see the theoretical probability to have an observation less than or equal to 0.2 using the punif function. \[P(X \leq 0.2)\]

> punif(0.2, min = 0, max = 2)
[1] 0.1

\[P(X > 0.2)\]

> punif(0.2, min = 0, max = 2, lower.tail = FALSE)
[1] 0.9

By using the qunif function, for the same random variable \(X\), we can compute the theoretical \(0.6\) quantile. It is the smallest number where the cumulative distribution function (CDF) is bigger than or equal to \(0.6\). \[X_{0.6} = min\{x \in \mathbb{R} : P(X \leq x) \geq 0.6\} = \] \[ = p(b - a) + a = 0.6(2 - 0) + 0 = 1.2\]

> qunif(0.6, min = 0, max = 2)
[1] 1.2

Exponential distribution /Експоненциално разпределение/

Exponential distribution is the probability distribution of the time between events in a Poisson point process. \[X \in Exp(\lambda)\]

Cumulative distribution function (CDF) \[F_X(x) = 1 - e^{-\lambda x}, \quad x > 0\] For \(p \in (0, 1)\) \[1 - e^{-\lambda x} = p\] \[1 - p = e^{-\lambda x}\] \[ln(1 - p) = -\lambda x\] \[x = -\frac{ln(1 - p)}{\lambda}\] therefore

Quantile function \[X_p = F_X^{\leftarrow}(p) = min\{x \in \mathbb{R} : P(X \leq x) \geq p\} = -\frac{ln(1 - p)}{\lambda}\]

Probability density function (PDF) \[f_X(x) = \lambda e^{-\lambda x}, \quad x > 0\]

Mean \[\mu = \frac{1}{\lambda}\] Variance \[\sigma^2 = \frac{1}{\lambda^2}\]

We can use the functions dexp, rexp, pexp and qexp to find the theoretical probability density function, to generate random numbers, to find the cumulative distribution function and quantiles of exponentially distributed random variable.

Example

The average life of a bulb is \(2\) years. Simulate the length of the life of \(100\) bulbs and summarize the results. \[X \in Exp \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)\]

> x <- rexp(100, 1/2)
> summary(x)
    Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
0.004218 0.771401 1.568457 2.198680 2.897103 9.548184 
> hist(x, probability = TRUE, col = gray(.9), main = "Exponential distributed with mean = 2")
> curve(dexp(x, 1/2), add = TRUE, col = "red")

We can calculate the skewness and kurtosis of the sample.

> skewness(x)
[1] 1.595264
> kurtosis(x)
[1] 2.234495

As we can see the skewness is positive, because the exponential distribution is right-skewed. As far as the kurtosis is positive, the distribution is leptokurtic.

The theoretical probability a bulb to live less than or equal to \(1.5\) years could be found by using the pexp function. \[P(X \leq 1.5) = 1 - e^{-2*1.5} \approx 0.9502\]

> pexp(1.5, rate = 2)
[1] 0.9502129

A bulb to live more than \(1.5\) years \[P(X > 1.5)\]

> pexp(1.5, rate = 2, lower.tail = FALSE)
[1] 0.04978707

\[P(X > 1.5) = 1 - P(X \leq 1.5)\]

> 1 - pexp(1.5, rate = 2)
[1] 0.04978707

What is the \(0.6\) quantile of this distribution or with other words what is the length of the life that will be reached by \(60%\) of the bulbs. \[X_{0.6} = min\{x \in \mathbb{R} : P(X \leq x) \geq 0.6\} = \] \[ = -\frac{ln(1 - p)}{\lambda} = -\frac{ln(1 - 0.6)}{2} \approx 0.4581\]

> qexp(0.6, rate = 2)
[1] 0.4581454

Gamma distribution /Гама разпределение/

Gamma distribution is a generalization of the exponential distribution. \[X \in \Gamma(\alpha, \beta)\]

Probability density function (PDF) There are two parametrizations of gamma distribution. The first one is via the rate parameter \(\beta > 0\). The second one is via the scale parameter \(\theta = \frac{1}{\beta} > 0\). \[f_X(x) = \frac{\beta^\alpha}{\Gamma(\alpha)} x^{\alpha-1} e^{-\beta x} = \frac{1}{\theta^\alpha \Gamma(\alpha)} x^{\alpha-1} e^{-\frac{x}{\theta}}, \quad x > 0\] where \[\Gamma(\alpha) = \int_{0}^{+\infty}{x^{\alpha-1} e^{-x} dx}, \quad \Gamma(n) = (n-1)!\] and \(\alpha > 0\) is called shape parameter.

\[\Gamma(1, \beta) \equiv Exp(\beta)\]

Mean \[\mu = \frac{\alpha}{\beta}\] Variance \[\sigma^2 = \frac{\alpha}{\beta^2}\]

We can use the functions dgamma, rgamma, pgamma and qgamma to find the theoretical probability density function, to generate random numbers, to find the cumulative distribution function and quantiles of gamma distributed random variable.

Example

The average life in years of a bulb is gamma distributed with shape parameter \(5\) and rate parameter \(3\). Simulate the length of the life of \(100\) bulbs and summarize the results. Compute the expected length of the life and its variance. \[X \in \Gamma(5, 3)\]

> x <- rgamma(100, shape = 5, rate = 3)
> summary(x)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
 0.2271  1.0800  1.5388  1.6496  2.1403  3.3546 
> hist(x, probability = TRUE, col = gray(.9), main = "Gamma distributed with shape = 5 and rate = 3")
> curve(dgamma(x, shape = 5, rate = 3), add = TRUE, col = "red")

\[E[X] = \frac{\alpha}{\beta} = \frac{5}{3} \approx 1.67\] \[D[X] = \frac{\alpha}{\beta^2} = \frac{5}{3^2} \approx 0.56\]

> var(x)
[1] 0.5181091

We can calculate the skewness and kurtosis of the sample.

> skewness(x)
[1] 0.4217588
> kurtosis(x)
[1] -0.5214291

As we can see the skewness is positive, because the gamma distribution \(\Gamma(5, 3)\) is right-skewed. As far as the kurtosis is positive, the distribution is leptokurtic.

The theoretical probability a bulb to live less than or equal to \(1.5\) years could be found by using the pgamma function. \[P(X \leq 1.5)\]

> pgamma(1.5, shape = 5, rate = 3)
[1] 0.4678964

A bulb to live more than \(1.5\) years \[P(X > 1.5)\]

> pgamma(1.5, shape = 5, rate = 3, lower.tail = FALSE)
[1] 0.5321036

\[P(X > 1.5) = 1 - P(X \leq 1.5)\]

> 1 - pgamma(1.5, shape = 5, rate = 3)
[1] 0.5321036

What is the \(0.6\) quantile of this distribution or with other words what is the length of the life that will be reached by \(60%\) of the bulbs. \[X_{0.6} = min\{x \in \mathbb{R} : P(X \leq x) \geq 0.6\}\]

> qgamma(0.6, shape = 5, rate = 3)
[1] 1.745539

Normal distribution /Нормално разпределение/

The normal distribution is defined by the Probability density function (PMF) equation \[f_X(x) = \frac{1}{\sigma \sqrt{2 \pi}} e^{-\frac{(x - \mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}}, \quad x \in \mathbb R\]

\[X \in N(\mu, \sigma^2)\] Mean \[\mu = E[X]\] Variance \[\sigma^2 = D[X]\] We can use the functions dnorm, rnorm, pnorm and qnorm to find the theoretical probability density function, to generate random numbers, to find the cumulative distribution function and quantiles of normal distributed variable.

Let’s generate a realization of \(N(100,16^2)\) random variable.

> rnorm(1, mean = 100, sd = 16)
[1] 101.9347

Let’s generate a realization of \(N(100,10^2)\) random variable.

> rnorm(1, mean = 280, sd = 10)
[1] 281.8108

Let’s generate \(1000\) realizations of \(N(0,1^2)\) random variable.

> x <- rnorm(1000)
> hist(x, probability = TRUE, col = gray(.9), main = "Standart normal distribution")
> curve(dnorm(x), add = TRUE, col = "red")

Let’s generate \(1000\) realizations of \(N(100,16^2)\) random variable.

> x <- rnorm(1000, mean = 100, sd = 16)
> hist(x, probability = TRUE, col = gray(.9), main = "Normal distribution with mu = 100, sigma = 16")
> curve(dnorm(x, mean = 100, sd = 16), add = TRUE, col = "red")

We can calculate the skewness and kurtosis of the sample.

> skewness(x)
[1] -0.03903337
> kurtosis(x)
[1] 0.003985516

As we can see the skewness is approximately \(0\), because the normal distribution is symmetric. As far as the kurtosis is almost \(0\), the distribution is mesokurtic.

Let’s generate \(1000\) realizations of \(N(100,106^2)\) random variable.

> x <- rnorm(1000, mean = 100, sd = 106)
> hist(x, probability = TRUE, col = gray(.9), main = "Normal distribution with mu = 100, sigma = 106")
> curve(dnorm(x, mean = 100, sd = 106), add = TRUE, col = "red")

z-scores

\[\text{Z-score}(x_i) = \frac{x_i - \mu}{\sigma}\]

> mean.x <- 100; sd.x <- 16
> x <- rnorm(5, mean.x, sd.x); x
[1] 123.07510  70.83086  89.26677 120.52931 101.92490
> z.score = (x - mean.x) / sd.x; z.score
[1]  1.4421935 -1.8230714 -0.6708272  1.2830819  0.1203060

Chi-squared distribution /Хи квадрат разпределение/

\[X \in \chi^2(n)\] Chi-squared distribution is a particular case of gamma distribution. More precisely \[\Gamma(\frac{n}{2}, \frac{1}{2}) \equiv \chi^2(n) \]

\(\chi^2\) distribution with \(n\) degrees of freedom is the distribution of a sum of the squares of \(n\) independent standard normal variables \[X_1, \: X_2, \: …, \: X_n \in N(0, 1) \: iid \: \Rightarrow X_1^2 + X_2^2 + ... + X_n^2 \in \chi^2(n)\]

Mean \[\mu = n\] Variance \[\sigma^2 = 2n\]

We can use the functions dchisq, rchisq, pchisq and qchisq to find the theoretical probability density function, to generate random numbers, to find the cumulative distribution function and quantiles of chi-square distributed variable.

> x <- rchisq(1000, 10)
> hist(x, probability = TRUE, col = gray(.9), main = "Chi-square with 10 degrees of freedom")
> curve(dchisq(x, 10), add = TRUE, col = "red")

We can calculate the skewness and kurtosis of the sample.

> skewness(x)
[1] 0.9413891
> kurtosis(x)
[1] 1.217425

As we can see the skewness is positive, because the \(\chi^2\) distribution is right-skewed. As far as the kurtosis is positive, the distribution is leptokurtic.

Example:

> pchisq(0.7, df = 5)
[1] 0.01703132
> pchisq(0.7, df = 5, lower.tail = FALSE)
[1] 0.9829687
> qchisq(0.75, df = 5)
[1] 6.62568

Student’s t-distribution /t разпределение/

Student’s t-distribution was developed by William Sealy Gosset under the pseudonym Student. It can be used when the population proportion is normal and the sample size is under \(30\). \[X \in t(\nu)\] Where \(\nu = \text{sample size} - 1\) and is called degrees of freedom.

Probability density function (PDF)

Mean \[\mu = 0\] Variance \[\sigma^2 = \frac{\nu}{\nu - 2}\]

We can use the functions dt, rt, pt and qt to find the theoretical probability density function, to generate random numbers, to find the cumulative distribution function and quantiles of student-t distributed variable.

> x <- rt(1000, 10)
> hist(x, probability = TRUE, col = gray(.9), main = "Student t with 10 degrees of freedom")
> curve(dt(x, 10), add = TRUE, col = "red")

We can calculate the skewness and kurtosis of the sample.

> skewness(x)
[1] -0.04315149
> kurtosis(x)
[1] 0.2738327

As we can see the skewness is approximately \(0\), because the student-t distribution is symmetric. As far as the kurtosis is positive, the distribution is leptokurtic.
